  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. This includes:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Understanding customer financial activities\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR)\n- Identifying and reporting unusual transactions\n- Filing reports with financial crime enforcement agencies\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Establishing internal policies and procedures\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n- Training staff on money laundering detection\n\n4. Record keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Documenting customer information\n- Retaining records for specified periods\n\n5. Transaction monitoring\n- Tracking large or unusual financial activities\n- Using automated systems to detect potential money laundering\n\n6. International cooperation\n- Complying with global anti-money laundering standards\n- Sharing information across jurisdictions\n\n7. Potential penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal liability\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced through regulations like the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and similar laws internationally.",
